poolability test (it is different from Restricted f test) H0: coefficients for each variable are the same across all cross-sectional units, implying that the data is “poolable.” H1: data is not poolable

here, H0 is rejected and therefore pooled model won’t be stable

pooltest(MPS1~PAT1+EPS1+RR1+ROE1+DY2+DPS2,data=wpdata,model="within")
## 
##  F statistic
## 
## data:  MPS1 ~ PAT1 + EPS1 + RR1 + ROE1 + DY2 + DPS2
## F = 6.4555, df1 = 294, df2 = 200, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: unstability

Test for presence of individual and time effect in panel data

#twoways means we are testing for significance of both individual and time specific effects at once. “ghm” stands for gourieroux, holly and monfort test from the LM test family

Yit=μ+βXit+αi+λt+ηit

where, αi= individual specific effect λt= time specific effect

H0: no significant individual and time effect H1: significant individual and time effect clearly, p value is less than 0.05 implying that HO is rejected

plmtest(MPS1~PAT1+EPS1+RR1+ROE1+DY2+DPS2,data=wpdata,effect="twoways",type="ghm")
## 
##  Lagrange Multiplier Test - two-ways effects (Gourieroux, Holly and
##  Monfort)

## 0.50, w2 = 0.25, p-value < 2.2e-16

Diagnostic tests

1)Test of autocorrelation

a)DW statistic RANGES FROM 0-4 In general, DW=2 indicates no autocorrelation DW<2 indicates positive autorcorrelation DW>2 indicates negative autocorrelation H0- No autocorrelation in error term p value<0.05 then reject h0

clearly, idiosyncratic error term has autocorrelation

pdwtest(MPS1~PAT1+EPS1+RR1+ROE1+DY2+DPS2,data=wpdata,model="within")
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test for serial correlation in panel models
## 
## data:  MPS1 ~ PAT1 + EPS1 + RR1 + ROE1 + DY2 + DPS2
## DW = 0.99289, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: serial correlation in idiosyncratic errors

1.b) Wooldridge test for autocorrelation step1: save the model result(we shall use fem) step2: pbgtest(fem_model) H0:there is no autocorrelation in error term

clearly, we have autocorrelation

pbgtest(fem_model)
## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey/Wooldridge test for serial correlation in panel models

## data:  MPS1 ~ PAT1 + EPS1 + RR1 + ROE1 + DY2 + DPS2

## alternative hypothesis: serial correlation in idiosyncratic errors

Treating Heteroscedaticity and autocorrelation through ARELLANO-BOND model (standard error is made robust)

step1: save the results of fem or rem(which ever is the significant one by just running the model) step2: when there is only heteroscedasticity coeftest(fem_model,vcovHC) when there is both Heteroscedasticity and autocorrelation coeftest(fem_model,vcovHC(fem_model,method=“arellano”))

since we have both Heteroscedasticity and autocorrelation, we use arellano bond method.

fem_arellano<-coeftest(fem_model,vcovHC(fem_model,method="arellano"))

3)Test for cross sectional dependence in panel data.

Cross-sectional dependence in panel data occurs when the observations (e.g., individuals, firms, countries) are not independent of each other across the cross-section (i.e., at a single point in time) as per Baltagi, cross sectional dependence is a problem of macro panels(t>i) with long time seires. This is not a problem in micro panels(i>t).

we can check C.S dependence through: a) Breusch-pagan LM test for C.S dependence b) pesaranCD for C.S dependence

H0:there is no cross-sectional dependence

clearly, we have C.S dependence as per both tests.

pcdtest(fem_model,test=c("lm")) #BP TEST
## 
##  Breusch-Pagan LM test for cross-sectional dependence in panels
## 
## data:  MPS1 ~ PAT1 + EPS1 + RR1 + ROE1 + DY2 + DPS2
## chisq = 3890.1, df = 1225, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: cross-sectional dependence
pcdtest(fem_model,test=c("cd")) #pesarancd test
## 
##  Pesaran CD test for cross-sectional dependence in panels
## 
## data:  MPS1 ~ PAT1 + EPS1 + RR1 + ROE1 + DY2 + DPS2
## z = 21.562, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: cross-sectional dependence

4)stationarity test using ADF test(library-tseries)

H0: data is non-stationary.

the two thing we look for in adf test(urca): (a)if adf “test statistic value” falls after taking a difference then T.S is stationary at that diff. (b)also p value at that difference must be < 0.05 note: “trend” in ADF test includes both trend and drift components

adf.test(wpdata$MPS1,k=2)
